The paper deals with the approximation of functions using deep neural networks and establishes lower bounds on the connectivity and memory requirements of such networks. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) or Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses numerical experiments involving stochastic gradient descent, which is a common optimization algorithm used in machine learning. This further supports the possibility of the paper belonging to the Machine Learning sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of representation systems such as wavelets, ridgelets, and shearlets, which are commonly used in image processing and computer vision. This suggests that the paper could also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Finally, the paper briefly mentions the extension of their results to functions on low-dimensional immersed manifolds, which could potentially place the paper in the Scientific Computing (cs.NA) or Symmetric Functions (cs.SI) sub-categories.
